At March 31, 2009, Bartow County Bank owned common stock issued by Silverton Bank, N.A. with a net book value of $1,995,765. On May 1, 2009, the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency closed Silverton Bank, N.A. and the FDIC was named as receiver. The loss on the investment is recorded on line RI-5.k "Net gains (losses) on sales of other assets". This Call Report is amended for an additional provision to the Allowance for Loan Losses and writedowns on other real estate. Additionally, Tier 1 capital is impacted by the disallowance of a portion of the Deferred Tax Asset.

359360	835	25	452	336	CONF	62	79	0	2979	1760	879	0	0	0	0	0	0	23000	0	3706	0	true	142	-1652	0	132	52	316	1577	558	0	0	223	1934	12	886	0	0	Credit Card Inocme	Customer Service Fees		Servicing expenses by affiliate	ORE/Rep Asset Expense	Other Loan Expense				Capital Contributions		Business Combinations		First Community Bank, N.A. completed a review of goodwill for impairment during the year ended December 31, 2009. Goodwill represents the net fair value of consideration given in excess of the fair value of the net assets of the acquired banks at the date of acquisition less any identifiable intangibles. The Bank tests its goodwill for impairment annually or between annual tests, if an event occurs or circumstances change that would indicate the carrying value may be impaired. The Bank recognized an impairment loss on goodwill of $37,396 million. This charge reflects recent bank holding company stock transactions, declines in market values of peer banks in Texas and a weaker economic outlook in the state. The loss is a noncash accounting adjustment to the Bank's balance sheet that does not affect regulatory and tangible capital ratios. The goodwill impairment loss entirely eliminates the Bank's goodwill at period end. While this charge increased reported net loss and reduced total assets, it had no impact on key capital ratios. Rental Bldg Exp	Loss Expense for Real Estate								The $504 change to equity is a change in accounting method to move from the income tax baisis of depreciation to the GAAP basis of depreciation. The offset of this change effects accumulated depreciation and deferred taxes.  The deferred tax liability increases by $260 for Federal Deferred Taxes and $35 for State Deferred Taxes. After this adjustment, total deferred taxes decreases due to the current income tax adjustment. Deferred taxes then become a deferred tax asset on Schedule RC-F. In March 2007, the Bank received a one time allocation of $8.6 million in overhead. Effective 4/1/07, the Bank has entered into an agreement with its parent which states that the parent agrees not to allocate any overhead to the Bank until its net income, after allocation exceeds $2 million for a period of three years. Legg Mason Investment Council & Trust Company, NA ("Bank") now assesses and monitors its capital, capital needs and liquidity on a quarterly basis through its Investment Policy Committee. The Income and Expense sheet, Balance Sheet and Tier 1 Capital is reviewed monthly. The Investment Policy Committee minutes are submitted to the Board of Directors. In addition, as part of the quarterly financial review, the Bank's capital and liquidity is reviewed by the Board.

Based on the estimated future earnings and the expiration of the net operating loss carryforwards we have determined that it is more likely than not that the deferred tax assets will not be realized in the near term. Push-down purchase accounting created a Core Deposit Intangible asset in the amount of $1,120,000.  This intangible asset is amortized in accordance with GAAP and expensed resulting in a significant reduction in the reported earnings of the bank.  The earnings impact for the first 12-month period beginning 9/1/08 was $367,000.  The earnings impact for the second 12-month period beginning 9/1/09 is estimated to be $249,000. Accordingly in order to determine the tangible earnings of the bank, line 7.c.2. of schedule RI should be added back to the reported net income on line 14 of the same schedule.	Based on audit, push-down accounting adjustment from the 9/1/09 sale of the bank.

The implementation of this accounting principal requires the Bank to reclassify that portion of non-credit losses associated with investment securities, recorded through the income statement in 2008, out of beginning retained earnings on January 1, 2009 and into other comprehensive income.
